<br>
1st - You already admitted to not having your ae stuns up so..shame on you!!  I never went anywhere when experienceing without at least 2 color stuns up. They are just too valuable and will save your butt. <br>
<br>
2nd - AE mes is a great spell.....unless you dont have color stuns to back you up on resists. A resist on ae mes means you have a mob beating on you still and only have about 22 seconds to remez the others.(length of ae mes - spell cast time). This is ok with color stuns up but not without.<br>
<br>
3rd - Every member of a group is responsible for whats happening. One of those druids shoud be watching you like a hawk. Since they have no stuns like a cleric, they should of fired off a root or healed you. This would of drawn aggro away from you and given you a chance to regain control.<br>
<br>
4th - How did you draw aggro in the first place? If I had no stuns up on spell lineup I would be very carefuly about what aggros me. I would use single target spells Until I got the situation under control of realized I had no stun loaded and loaded it fast.( remember the page numbers these are on. If your quick during battle you can sit and grab the spell icon before you are forced back up. I used to do this occasionally when I didnt have a certain spell loaded. Yes you are gonna take max damage but if the situation requires it be used, Im not losing anything.)<br>
<br>
5th - We used to have to teach members of a group how to work with an enchanter. Most people just didnt understand the concepts until lvl 30ish or so. This is still true for any non twinks. However, now that I am involved with pickup groups again, I have found that a lot of clerics, druids, wizads, and shaman even around my level(60) do not crowd control. We need to educate the other classes on the value of stuns and roots.  Any class that has the ability to root, charm, or stun is also responsible for helping with crowd control. The best clerics will have their stuns and roots loaded during battle and use them to help you crowd control. Druids will use their roots/snares and speed(outside groups) to draw aggro and kite mobs away. Shaman will root mobs and nuke the crap out of a mob til it aggros them. Then they will just tank the mob until the chanter can deal with it more permanantly. Warriors or other tanks can even play a role in crowd control by simple tanking a mob until you can deal with it. This is hard for some people to understand because it may require that they die to deal with the problem.  But its better for one person to die then the whole group. Experience can still flow until that char gets a res or runs back. <br>
<br>
6th - I know you are too low but this is just a good all around suggestion for everyone. Keep allure wands from fear on you at all times! They have saved my ass more times then I can count in sticky situations.<br>
<br>
So in your situation, since the mobs were beating on you already, you probably did the best you could. casting AE mes was the right call.<br>
<br>
<br>
finally, some recommendations on your spell lineup:<br>
The only two debuffs you need to load is tash and slow. The others are pretty useless against mobs. They are only really useful in pvp when you are debuffing the strenght of a char so they cant move. I would recommend you dump the debuffs, even when a shaman is not around. My recommended spell lineup to anyone below fifty would be this:<br>
<br>
1)mes<br>
2)ae mes<br>
3)color stun<br>
4)color stun<br>
5)tash<br>
6)slow - with a shaman can be substituted for charm.<br>
7)root<br>
