<i>1: Tepid Deeds<br>
2: Insipid Weakness<br>
3: Listless Power<br>
4: usually AE Stun.. but at the time was Random something<br>
5 Clarity/Haste<br>
6 AE Mez<br>
7 Tash<br>
8 Enthrall (Might've been to entrance.. I forget when I decided it was resisted too much and went back to enthrall)</i><br>
<br>
Now, we all have our own way of doing things, but your spell lineup could use some work, I think.<br>
<br>
The five top slots that I use, which are practically inviolate are:<br>
<br>
1) Root<br>
2) Mez<br>
3) 20 stun<br>
4) 4 stun<br>
5) tash<br>
<br>
These are the bread and butter crowd control tools. <br>
<br>
Why root?<br>
<br>
Judicious use of root is a key crowd control skill. It stops runners, saves healers and nukers from overaggro... the utility uses are endless. Learn to keep a root memed at all times and learn to use it. Root will save your life a thousand times over.<br>
<br>
Why mez?<br>
<br>
Well, duh. This is how the vast majority of enchanters do crowd control. A very few prefer charm as their primary crowd control tool, but charming is high risk and unpredictable, while mez is low risk and very predictable.<br>
<br>
Why 20 stun?<br>
<br>
Your 20th level stun gives you enough time with some slack and without moving to slip in a mez or a root on a mob that is beating on you. Before you channeling becomes absurd in your highest levels, slipping in a stun gives you the time to cast that mez, even when multiple mobs are beating on you.<br>
<br>
Also, your PBAE stun is a damage mitigation tool. When your healers are screaming oom, casting your PBAE stun in range of the offending mob can save lives.<br>
<br>
You can stop runners with stunning if you are quick and well positioned.<br>
<br>
Lastly, when a break still results in aggro to you, stunning buys the taunting tank time to taunt it off you with damage or with their taunt ability. While stun does create aggro, the damage put out by the tank will offset this.<br>
<br>
Why 4 stun?<br>
<br>
The major benefit of the level 4 stun is its 1.0 casting time. You can get a level 4 stun inbetween the swings of a non-hasted mob with ease. Unless your connection is good and you have the speed to get range from a mob that is aggroed on you it isn't enough time to slip in a mez or root (( until you get immobilize, which has a low enough cast time to get in the time alloted by a 4 stun )) BUT, the 4 stun gives you the time to cast your 20 stun with ease and in style.<br>
<br>
So when a mob is aggroed on you, you cast your 4 stun, when it lands, you cast your 20 stun, and then you attempt to mez it. If you are resisted, the 4 stun has just about recycled by that time, giving you another bite at the apple.<br>
<br>
When more than one mob is beating on you, the fast cast of a level 4 stun may be what saves your life, becase you may not be able to channel through a 20 stun or mez through the damage and bashing.<br>
<br>
Why tash?<br>
<br>
Tash is our MR debuff. All our spells except for one and the tash line itself are magic based resist. Many utility spells such as snare, slow, root, and fear and many lines of damaging spells are also MR based. Tash helps the efficency of the group by reducing resist and increasing damage on MR based nuke + dot lines.<br>
<br>
Tash does create a lot of aggro, so learning the timing of it is the key to it's proper use. Don't tash mobs that haven't been aggroed on INC, because they will aggro you... it is better that they aggro the puller or one of the other tanks on INC because they are more equipped both HP and AC wise to handle a few stray blows while you get things under control.<br>
<br>
The exception to this is when mobs are very red to you and/or highly MR. You may want to tash first, which will give you at least a shot at landing a mez on the offending creature, while just a mez without tash would give you close to a zero chance of landing a mez.<br>
<br>
As to your other spells, I suggest a slow, a buff/nuke swap slot, and either AE mez or charm, depending on what your are comfortable with.<br>
<br>
Why slow?<br>
<br>
Slow increases the group efficency dramatically. It reduces damage output, which means that healing mana is saved. If the healers have mana, you can pull more. If you can pull more, you get more xp. This makes everyone happy.<br>
<br>
Also, if mobs are slowed, if they aggro on you because you mistime a mez or because there is an inadvertent break of mez, or if they charge you despite the efforts of your tanks, they will do less damage to you, there will be more time inbetween their swings, giving you more chances to deal with the situation though root or stun.<br>
<br>
Why a buff slot?<br>
<br>
While the duration of your current haste isn't all that great, if you have it cycled, you still only need to pull it out every 14 mins or so. There isn't a lot of point keeping it memed all the time. You can put the slot to better use.<br>
<br>
Same with clarity or other assorted buffs like our AC buff, a WIS/INT buff or cha. They aren't needed all the time, so it is best to pull it out only when you need it.<br>
<br>
When you don't need the slot for buffing, try meming a nuke if you have mana to spare on it. It can help increase kill rate to chip in some damage. While our nukes are not time or aggro efficent, they can help. Plus it is fun to blast away once in a while.<br>
<br>
Why AE mez or charm?<br>
<br>
I feel more comfortable with charm, never really liking AE mez as I leveled except for specific situations, but some people thrive on AE mez... so if that is a tool you feel comfortable using, keep it handy. <br>
<br>
Charm can add a lot of risk to a group, but the reward in added damage can bring a lot too.<br>
<br>
Why not stat debuffs?<br>
<br>
They are mana inefficent. They don't seem to provide a lot of benefit for their mana expenditure. They bring a disproportionate amount of aggro on to you by their casting for their effect. By the time you have fully debuffed a mob that your party is working on, they are probably mostly dead at that point.<br>
<br>
If you have spare mana, try nuking the blue cons instead. A tashed blue con of average MR won't resist you that much, and you can lop off a fair chuck of their HP with just one blast. <br>
<br>
Why not mana seive?<br>
<br>
In OT I can't think of any casters you would be pulling, so there isn't any real reason to seive them. Seive is more of a strategic tool in raid situations and specific post 55 mobs. You really shouldn't be using it, because it will take vast amounts of your mana to seive down even run-of-the-mill casters at your level. Stun them to stop their casting instead. Encourage your cleric and wizard to do the same.<br>
<br>
What should I be doing in a group?<br>
<br>
Single mobs:<br>
<br>
The puller will tell your group what is INC.<br>
<br>
The main tank will engage the mob, give them a moment to build some aggro. It may take you some time to learn how much aggro that particular tank can draw in a given amount of time based on their level and weapon selection. One thing to note is that the taunt skill is mostly ineffective on mobs that con highly to the tank in question. Moderate your timing accordingly.<br>
<br>
Cast a tash. Hopefully your snarer has learned not to cast snare immediately upon the mob's arrival... because around 30 mobs start to really hate being snared and they will often draw aggro. If you are tashing religiously and your snarer isn't waiting for it, have a little heart to heart with them in /tell so that you can coordinate your spells. Call out your tash in the beginning of unknown group situations, but when things are running smoothly, you don't need to call it out anymore because people will expect you to be doing your job and they theirs.<br>
<br>
Once your tash has landed and you do not have aggro, if you are the slower, cast your slow. It will probably land on the first try on a tashed mob. If it doesn't, pause a bit to let the tanks take some more aggro, gauge to see if slowing this mob will be mana efficent based on it's remaining HP and try slowing it again.<br>
<br>
If you are not the slower, because you have a shaman, try blasting the mob if you have mana to spare when it is below 50%. If your tanks are building adequate aggro, you shouldn't have any problems about drawing aggro with your nuking. Two nukes is usually excessive, though.<br>
<br>
If you have a shaman, you can help share the slowing duties with them. Our slows aren't that different in power at that point, and if the shaman is performing healing buffing and other duites, being able to use your mana helps keep the mana levels of the group balanced. Your mana should be around the same as the healers and nukers mana in a good xp group. This shows that people are using the correct amount of mana for a given situation, yet still have a reserve for unexpected circumstances. If you have a lot more mana than the healers, try blasting more. If you have a lot less mana than the healers, you may be coming off a buff cycle, or you may be slowing too much. Every Single Mob doesn't need to be slowed, it typically wears you out and leaves you with little mana, and if the group has sufficent DPS and levels to deal with what is coming at a goodly clip, the healers may be overflowing with mana.<br>
<br>
The mob dies, someone loots, and you start over.<br>
<br>
Multiple mobs:<br>
<br>
If there are multiple mobs INC, hopefully the puller will tell you so you can stand up. Learning to stand up on INC mobs is a good habit, because you aquire a substantial amount of aggro in certain situations from sitting. Because you are out-of-doors, target a mob as soon as you can and mez it as soon is it comes within range. Spam your mez key so you can get the spell started at the maximum possible range. If you are not resisted, great! Target any other mobs and mez them too.<br>
<br>
If you are resisted, try to slip in another mez. You probably won't be able to complete the casting before the mob engages you, but you can get most of the spell complete, giving you a good shot at channeling it though. If this isn't successful, womp it with your level 4 stun, and then your level 20 stun, and then mez it. If you are resisted yet again, channel through a tash and try stunning it again. If your other group members are smart and aware and see you in distress, they may support your efforts by rooting or stunning the mob themselves. This buys you time to try to land another mez or back away and mez it at your leisure.<br>
<br>
Positioning:<br>
<br>
It is good to stand a bit away from your group. Aggro, based on mobs, is somewhat proximity based, so standing a bit away from your group helps keep aggro from your healers. Also, if you stand back and away a bit, if give you a clean line of sight to mez mobs as they are incoming. Finally, sometimes pullers will pull mobs across groups, and you don't want to be sitting in their midst and getting hit as they go by because of sitting aggro.<br>
<br>
On the mez break:<br>
<br>
Stand on mez breaks.<br>
<br>
Don't be in melee range of the mob.<br>
<br>
Don't berate your tanks if you get charged after a break. They are probably doing all they can, but they may not have the level to hold aggro with taunt during a break.<br>
<br>
Do debuff your mezzed mobs situationally. Tash them. Slow them. Anything more than that is excessive and probably wasted mana. If your meleers are having trouble taking aggro after a break, don't debuff the mobs... wait until the MT has built some aggro after break.<br>
<br>
Let the melees and other classes know what skills they can use to help on breaks. Paladins can stun and root. SKs can cast a dizzying array of dots and debuffs which create lots of aggro. Clerics and wizards can stun the mob on break if it shows signs of running at you (( or a healer! )), giving the tanks some more swings and opportunities to taunt. Mages can use an air or earth pet. Aggro control is a community effort, and everyone can do their part.<br>
<br>
On AE mez when you are being thrashed:<br>
<br>
AE mez's cast time is slightly longer than regular mez. This gives more opportunity for mobs to beat on you, increasing your chances of interrupt. Also, you can mez yourself, which isn't so hot, but usually not the end of the world. I suggest using your stuns and single mezzing offending mobs thrashing on you rather than AE mezing.<br>
<br>
On dealing with snotty people who have high level chanters in your group:<br>
<br>
Tell them to /tell Olenari, and I'll set them to rights. =D<br>
